Using SPIDER for disease biomarker identification

Ruoqiao Chen

2024-09-06

The predicted surface protein abundance values obtained from SPIDER can be used for multiple downstream analysis. Here we provide an example of one downstream application of SPIDER: Disease biomarker identification.

First let’s load the SPIDER package:

library(SPIDER)

Download the demo scRNA-seq data here (this is a subset from the pre-processed data in this paper. For tutorial convenience we only use a subset of it). The data contain the transcriptomic data in single cells from human hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) patients and healthy controls.

We have already prepared the predicted surface protein abundance files obtained from SPIDER on the scRNA-seq demo data, you can download them here (this is to save your time for running the tutorial. Alternatively, you can also do it by yourself via the “SPIDER_predict” function).

Let’s read the predicted protein abundance files and protein confidence score files in R (the protein confidence score files are not used in this tutorial, generally a higher confidence score means that the protein is more likely to be predict accurately. In our paper, we use a threshold of confidence score of >0.85 for selecting highly-confident proteins. Users can also choose some other thresholds depending on their needs):

load('/Users/chenruo4/Desktop/test_SPIDER_package_user/SPIDER/downstream_applications/sample_query_for_downstream.RData')

seen_proteins_HCC <- read.csv('/Users/chenruo4/Downloads/predicted_protein_abundance_demo/HCC/demo/all_seen_proteins_predicted.csv', stringsAsFactors = F, row.names = 1, check.names = F)

unseen_proteins_HCC <- read.csv('/Users/chenruo4/Downloads/predicted_protein_abundance_demo/HCC/demo/all_unseen_proteins_predicted.csv', stringsAsFactors = F, row.names = 1, check.names = F)

confidence_HCC <- read.csv('/Users/chenruo4/Downloads/predicted_protein_abundance_demo/HCC/demo/confidence_score_all_unseen_proteins.csv', stringsAsFactors = F, row.names = 1, check.names = F)

seen_proteins_healthy <- read.csv('/Users/chenruo4/Downloads/predicted_protein_abundance_demo/healthy/demo/all_seen_proteins_predicted.csv', stringsAsFactors = F, row.names = 1, check.names = F)

unseen_proteins_healthy <- read.csv('/Users/chenruo4/Downloads/predicted_protein_abundance_demo/healthy/demo/all_unseen_proteins_predicted.csv', stringsAsFactors = F, row.names = 1, check.names = F)

confidence_healthy <- read.csv('/Users/chenruo4/Downloads/predicted_protein_abundance_demo/healthy/demo/confidence_score_all_unseen_proteins.csv', stringsAsFactors = F, row.names = 1, check.names = F)

data_combined <- merge(RNA_healthy, RNA_HCC)
data_combined[["ADT"]] <- CreateAssayObject(counts = cbind(rbind(seen_proteins_healthy, unseen_proteins_healthy), rbind(seen_proteins_HCC, unseen_proteins_HCC)))
data_combined@assays$ADT@data = data_combined@assays$ADT@counts
data_combined <- FindVariableFeatures(data_combined)
data_combined <- ScaleData(data_combined)
data_combined <- RunPCA(data_combined, verbose = FALSE)
data_combined <- FindNeighbors(data_combined, dims = 1:50)
data_combined <- FindClusters(data_combined, resolution = 0.5)

Having the predicted surface protein abundance data from SPIDER, we can identify HCC biomarkers in an interested cell type following a typical Seurat workflow. For instance, here we want to identify HCC biomarkers in γδ2 T cells:

tmp <- data_combined[, data_combined@meta.data$predicted.id == "γδ2.T.cells"]
markers <- FindMarkers(tmp, ident.1 = colnames(tmp)[tmp@meta.data$stim == 'Tumor'], ident.2 = colnames(tmp)[tmp@meta.data$stim == 'Control'], assay = "ADT")

head(markers)

We can visualize the SPIDER-predicted abundance of our interested HCC biomarker protein in all the cells. For example, we are interested in CD279 (i.e., PD-1), which is identified by SPIDER as a HCC biomarker in γδ2 T cells:

markers['CD279', ]
##              p_val avg_log2FC pct.1 pct.2    p_val_adj
## CD279 2.814262e-22  0.3616327     1     1 7.998133e-19
DefaultAssay(data_combined) <- "ADT"
FeaturePlot(data_combined, features = 'CD279', min.cutoff = "q05", max.cutoff = "q95")

DimPlot(data_combined, reduction = "umap",label=F,group.by='stim')

DimPlot(data_combined, reduction = "umap",label=F,group.by='predicted.id')

From the visualization, we can clearly see that PD-1 is predicted by SPIDER to be highly expressed in γδ2 T cells in HCC patient cells compared to healthy control cells, and PD-1 is identified as a HCC biomarker in γδ2 T cells via SPIDER prediction.
